12:22.382 --> 12:24.617
[Floorboards creaking]

12:28.088 --> 12:30.122
[Sighs]

12:30.157 --> 12:33.926
[Bag thuds]

12:34.961 --> 12:37.663
[Sighs]

12:42.636 --> 12:46.005
[Bag rustling]

12:55.415 --> 12:57.082
[Door creaks]

12:57.117 --> 12:58.784
[Dog barking in distance]

12:58.818 --> 13:00.819
[Bird cawing]

13:10.864 --> 13:11.897
[Door closes]

13:14.597 --> 13:17.699
Your Honor, the defense has made
the very reasonable request

13:17.733 --> 13:19.434
that the plaintiffs
produce their medical records

13:19.468 --> 13:21.369
or, barring that, a signed HIPAA release

13:21.403 --> 13:23.738
so that we can examine
the records ourselves.

13:23.772 --> 13:25.873
Your Honor, our clients' medical records

13:25.908 --> 13:28.076
have no bearing on the merits of this case.

13:28.110 --> 13:29.744
The medical records are plainly relevant,

13:29.778 --> 13:31.779
as they bear directly on our contention

13:31.814 --> 13:35.149
that the plaintiffs are not
adequate class representatives.

13:35.184 --> 13:37.552
This is a transparent
attempt at intimidation.

13:37.586 --> 13:39.765
- Nothing more.
- How so?

13:40.490 --> 13:42.124
Many of our clients have information

13:42.180 --> 13:44.227
in their medical records that
they prefer to keep private.

13:44.643 --> 13:46.244
They're fearful, as any of us would be,

13:46.278 --> 13:48.913
at the thought of a bunch of strangers
poking around in their personal files,

13:48.940 --> 13:50.807
and by forcing them
to reveal this information,

13:50.842 --> 13:53.877
the defense is banking on them
simply dropping out of the case.

13:53.911 --> 13:56.613
Your Honor, this is about class
certification. That's all.

13:56.648 --> 13:59.658
If the named plaintiffs
are suffering from dementia

13:59.877 --> 14:01.616
- or other mental deficiencies...
- You're saying they're incompetent?

14:01.654 --> 14:03.154
I'm saying we have the right to any record

14:03.188 --> 14:04.622
that would speak to their competency,

14:04.657 --> 14:06.057
as regards this class-certification issue.

14:06.104 --> 14:08.515
Your Honor, it seems that the defense
wants to have it both ways, then.

14:08.549 --> 14:10.183
If our clients are suffering from dementia,

14:10.217 --> 14:12.252
then the residency contracts
they signed with Sandpiper

14:12.286 --> 14:13.853
couldn't have been entered into knowingly.

14:13.888 --> 14:15.155
No, no. That is not what we're...

14:15.189 --> 14:16.456
The defense wants to claim

14:16.490 --> 14:18.258
that their residents are competent enough

14:18.292 --> 14:21.161
to be held to their contracts
but too incompetent to sue.

14:21.195 --> 14:22.695
So which is it?

14:22.730 --> 14:24.864
Many of the residents signed
their contracts years ago,

14:24.899 --> 14:27.500
and at the time,
they were perfectly competent.

14:27.535 --> 14:29.102
But that can change,

14:29.136 --> 14:31.538
especially when we're talking
about elderly individuals.

14:31.572 --> 14:34.107
Or maybe Sandpiper preyed
on mentally incompetent seniors

14:34.141 --> 14:35.775
and bilked them out of their money.

14:35.809 --> 14:37.043
Miss Wexler.

14:38.145 --> 14:40.380
I am simply trying to defend our clients

14:40.414 --> 14:42.148
from bullying by the defense.

14:42.183 --> 14:44.951
Your Honor, as stated
in the brief in front of you,

14:44.985 --> 14:46.619
this is a standard request,

14:46.654 --> 14:48.621
granted in every case of its kind.

14:48.656 --> 14:50.390
This is not about bullying.

14:50.424 --> 14:52.492
Granting this invasion of privacy

14:52.526 --> 14:55.128
allows our clients to be doubly victimized.

14:55.162 --> 14:58.198
I ask that you deny the
defense's motion, Your Honor.

14:58.232 --> 15:00.400
I'm leaning toward granting the motion,

15:00.434 --> 15:03.536
but I would like to review
the pleadings and briefs again.

15:03.571 --> 15:05.705
I'll have my decision for you shortly.

15:05.739 --> 15:07.507
Adjourned.

15:13.514 --> 15:15.715
I'm gonna meet you back at the office.

15:24.124 --> 15:26.659
Ms. Wexler. Hey.

15:26.694 --> 15:29.095
I just wanted to say, good work in there.

15:30.097 --> 15:31.998
Thanks, but I... I'm pretty sure I lost.

15:32.032 --> 15:34.334
Oh, of course you did.
It's an unwinnable position.

15:34.368 --> 15:36.502
That's why your boss
didn't bother showing up.

15:36.537 --> 15:39.505
But you went down swinging,
and I admire that.

15:39.540 --> 15:41.174
Thank you.

15:41.208 --> 15:43.109
What are you doing for lunch?

15:44.111 --> 15:47.113
Um, probably just grabbing something
from the vending machines.

15:47.147 --> 15:48.381
Oof.

15:48.415 --> 15:50.049
We can do better than that.

15:52.219 --> 15:53.786
Mr. Schweikart, good to see you, sir.

15:53.821 --> 15:55.455
- Ah, how you doing, Sean?
- Very well.

15:55.489 --> 15:57.857
Can I get some drinks for
you two? Your usual Moscow Mule?

15:57.891 --> 15:59.859
Absolutely. You want one?

15:59.893 --> 16:02.128
Best Moscow Mule in the city.

16:03.130 --> 16:06.199
Fresh ginger, real copper mug, the works.

16:06.233 --> 16:08.868
That's very vintage, but I'm good.

16:08.902 --> 16:10.203
Just an iced tea.

16:10.237 --> 16:11.571
Ah. You sure?

16:11.605 --> 16:13.106
All right, then.

16:13.140 --> 16:14.474
I'll be the sole degenerate

16:14.508 --> 16:16.109
who's drinking in the middle of a work day.

16:16.143 --> 16:18.111
That, too, is vintage.

16:18.145 --> 16:19.545
[Chuckles] I'll get those started.

16:19.580 --> 16:21.047
Mm.

16:21.081 --> 16:25.952
So, you've been with HHM, what... 10 years?

16:25.986 --> 16:29.289
Uh... Yeah, last August.

16:29.323 --> 16:31.791
And you started in the mail room?

16:31.825 --> 16:34.093
I did. I was six years there.

16:34.128 --> 16:35.461
How did you know that?

16:35.496 --> 16:37.163
Oh, I asked around. It's a small town.

16:37.197 --> 16:39.966
You know, it sounds like
you certainly paid your dues.

16:40.000 --> 16:41.501
I was very fortunate.

16:41.535 --> 16:43.670
HHM put me through law school
while I worked.

16:43.704 --> 16:46.172
That's great that
they foster talent like that.

16:46.206 --> 16:48.274
And I imagine you're paying it
off as part of your deal?

16:48.309 --> 16:49.509
Yeah, happily.

16:49.543 --> 16:50.910
It's a pretty standard arrangement.

16:50.944 --> 16:53.613
I have to say, watching you in court today,

16:53.647 --> 16:56.582
it sure did bring back
some old memories for me.

16:56.617 --> 16:58.351
One in particular, anyway.

16:58.385 --> 16:59.919
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

16:59.953 --> 17:02.155
I was a year out of law school
at this firm in Boston,

17:02.189 --> 17:03.790
and I was finally put
on my first big case...

17:03.824 --> 17:06.592
this huge employment-discrimination suit.

17:06.627 --> 17:09.095
That thing kept us in billing for a decade.

17:09.128 --> 17:11.464
Anyway, we landed this monster,

17:11.498 --> 17:14.032
and I find out I'm second chair
to one of the partners

17:14.068 --> 17:15.801
on the preliminary hearing,

17:15.836 --> 17:18.171
and I think, "This is it.

17:18.204 --> 17:21.140
This is what will define
the rest of my career."

17:21.175 --> 17:23.476
So, the hearing's getting closer and closer,

17:23.510 --> 17:25.877
I even get this new suit
that I can't afford...

17:25.913 --> 17:27.814
I split it over three credit cards.

17:27.848 --> 17:30.183
I'm probably still paying it off
to this day.

17:30.217 --> 17:31.718
[Chuckles]

17:31.752 --> 17:34.287
So, I go in bright and early,
I'm wearing my new suit,

17:34.321 --> 17:37.390
prepping my table, and in walks
the opposing counsel.

17:37.424 --> 17:40.949
There's four of them, one senior partner

17:41.009 --> 17:42.506
and three high-level associates.

17:42.529 --> 17:45.631
These guys have been litigating
longer than I've been alive.

17:45.666 --> 17:48.201
But I think, "Mm, I'm good.

17:48.235 --> 17:50.069
I got my boss coming.

17:50.104 --> 17:51.404
"It'll be fine."

17:51.438 --> 17:54.640
So, I'm sitting alone, at my table,

17:54.675 --> 17:57.143
waiting for my boss to show.

17:57.177 --> 17:58.544
And I'm waiting.

17:58.579 --> 18:00.046
And I'm waiting.

18:00.080 --> 18:02.181
And then, suddenly,
they're calling us to order,

18:02.216 --> 18:04.851
and I realize that no one
from my firm is coming.

18:04.885 --> 18:06.219
It's just me.

18:06.253 --> 18:08.221
So I think, "All right, then.

18:08.255 --> 18:09.889
This is the moment."

18:09.923 --> 18:13.393
And I get up there, and I argue
like my life depended on it.

18:13.427 --> 18:16.662
I'm sweating, and I'm citing
statutes left and right.

18:16.697 --> 18:18.064
And I'm doing okay.

18:18.098 --> 18:19.432
Respectable.

18:19.466 --> 18:22.702
But I'm just a BB gun
to these four howitzers.

18:24.905 --> 18:27.106
And I lose, of course.

18:27.141 --> 18:28.775
It was inevitable.

18:28.809 --> 18:30.843
But later, it hit me

18:30.878 --> 18:35.047
that my boss never intended to show.

18:35.082 --> 18:36.883
And they all laughed about it.

18:36.917 --> 18:39.552
They patted me on the back,
said it was my trial by fire,

18:39.586 --> 18:42.288
and I laughed with them, but, you know,

18:42.322 --> 18:44.690
it never really sat well with me.

18:44.725 --> 18:47.026
You want them to have your back.

18:47.060 --> 18:49.228
Because at the end of the day,

18:49.263 --> 18:51.697
it wasn't about proving my mettle.

18:51.732 --> 18:55.134
My boss had a tee time
that he didn't want to miss.

18:57.004 --> 18:58.738
I wasn't there long.

19:02.309 --> 19:05.912
Could I ask why we... are here?

19:05.946 --> 19:07.380
[Clears throat]

19:07.414 --> 19:10.283
You know, I've had my eye on you
for a while.

19:10.317 --> 19:11.884
Since that Kettleman thing.

19:11.919 --> 19:14.120
That was an excellent deal you got for him.

19:14.154 --> 19:16.289
And I'm wondering why someone

19:16.323 --> 19:18.991
who could put together a deal like that

19:19.026 --> 19:22.028
is arguing a losing position with no backup.

19:23.130 --> 19:26.132
I have no complaints about HHM.

19:26.166 --> 19:27.800
That's great.

19:27.835 --> 19:32.738
However, if on the off chance,
if you're pondering a change,

19:32.773 --> 19:34.507
Schweikart and Cokely
would be more than happy

19:34.541 --> 19:36.175
to put your talents to good use.

19:37.277 --> 19:38.678
Uh...

19:38.712 --> 19:40.313
Of course, we'd have to have
a more formal meeting,

19:40.347 --> 19:43.549
work out specifics, but we think
you would be a great fit.

19:47.788 --> 19:49.489
Well, I'm... I'm flattered,

19:49.523 --> 19:51.958
but there's clearly an ethical issue here.

19:51.992 --> 19:53.926
Well, of course,
we'd take you off Sandpiper.

19:53.961 --> 19:55.595
And rest assured,

19:55.629 --> 19:58.965
we wouldn't be expecting any
information about HHM strategy.

19:58.999 --> 20:01.701
Look, we're a large, diversified firm.

20:01.735 --> 20:05.104
And just think what you can do
with our resources

20:05.138 --> 20:08.207
and the freedom to really spread your wings.

20:11.812 --> 20:13.379
That's...

20:15.215 --> 20:17.283
I owe a lot to HHM.

20:17.317 --> 20:20.820
Your tuition debt? We can take care of that.

20:20.854 --> 20:22.588
That's very generous.

20:24.024 --> 20:25.958
Well, give it some time to think about it.

20:25.993 --> 20:28.227
And you give me a call,
and we'll set up a meeting

20:28.262 --> 20:31.364
with the rest of the senior partners.

20:31.398 --> 20:33.566
And to be clear...

20:33.600 --> 20:35.801
I'm talking partner track.

20:35.836 --> 20:38.004
Jesus, Sean, what... what'd
you have to send to Moscow?

20:38.038 --> 20:39.572
Hmm? [Chuckles]

20:39.606 --> 20:41.807
Sorry for the wait, Mr. Schweikart.

20:41.842 --> 20:43.609
Are we ready to order?

20:45.279 --> 20:47.813
[Crickets chirping]

20:47.848 --> 20:49.916
[Brakes squeal]

20:53.787 --> 20:56.055
[Engine shuts off]

21:38.966 --> 21:41.167
[Dog barks in distance]

21:48.442 --> 21:50.876
[Keys jingle]

21:50.911 --> 21:52.912
[Lock disengages]

21:56.984 --> 21:59.251
[Dog barks in distance]

21:59.286 --> 22:01.787
[Door creaks]

23:10.190 --> 23:13.926
[Refrigerator humming]

23:57.237 --> 23:58.938
[Remote clicks]

23:58.972 --> 24:01.207
<i>...Mays here for the Gourmet Quick Chop.</i>

24:01.241 --> 24:04.176
<i>It's the fastest, easiest, and safest way</i>

24:04.211 --> 24:07.012
<i>to chop, mince, or dice</i>
<i>any vegetable, guaranteed.</i>

24:07.047 --> 24:09.081
<i>Here's how it works.</i>

24:09.116 --> 24:11.450
- [Door creaks]
- [ <i> Quick Chop Commercial continues</i> ]

24:17.257 --> 24:19.125
Unh!

24:24.297 --> 24:26.298
- Get down.
- [Groans]

24:26.333 --> 24:27.900
Get down.

24:30.470 --> 24:33.405
[Man groaning]

24:46.987 --> 24:48.821
What's the message?

24:48.855 --> 24:50.890
Take the $5,000.

24:50.924 --> 24:53.025
It took two guys to tell me that?

24:55.362 --> 24:57.897
We were just supposed to
scare you, that's all.

24:57.931 --> 25:00.232
You try harder next time.

25:00.267 --> 25:01.801
Get out.

25:07.374 --> 25:08.874
MIKE: Get out!

25:10.277 --> 25:11.977
[Door creaks]

25:17.951 --> 25:20.319
♪

25:21.955 --> 25:25.691
[Sighs]

25:27.694 --> 25:31.463
♪

25:42.542 --> 25:46.712
[Sighs]

25:48.582 --> 25:52.351
♪

26:27.220 --> 26:30.956
♪

26:37.623 --> 26:39.490
[Telephone rings in background]

26:42.469 --> 26:44.103
[Knock on door]

26:44.137 --> 26:46.238
Oh, hey, Julie. Come on in.

26:46.272 --> 26:47.506
[Door creaks]

26:47.540 --> 26:49.341
I've got those Sandpiper documents.

26:49.375 --> 26:51.243
Great. Just put them anywhere.

26:51.277 --> 26:53.912
Howard asked if you could
go through them now.

26:53.947 --> 26:56.348
It's 1:15. I was just about
to grab some lunch.

26:56.382 --> 26:58.617
Yeah, he needs them done by 2:30
so he can draft a letter.

26:58.651 --> 27:00.185
I brought these.

27:00.220 --> 27:02.821
Figured I could petty-cash
a lunch order for you.

27:02.856 --> 27:05.691
I got accounting to approve
that new fancy salad place.

27:05.725 --> 27:10.662
[Indistinct conversations]

27:10.697 --> 27:12.698
[Telephone rings in distance]

27:24.077 --> 27:26.111
MIKE: Kaylee!

27:26.146 --> 27:27.379
Kaylee!

27:27.413 --> 27:30.048
Come on, not too far from the side.

27:30.083 --> 27:32.184
Throw the ball, Pop-Pop!

27:32.218 --> 27:33.886
Mm.

27:33.920 --> 27:35.554
[Chuckles]

27:37.357 --> 27:39.992
When are we going home?

27:40.026 --> 27:43.128
What? You don't like it here?

27:43.163 --> 27:45.063
It's okay.

27:45.098 --> 27:47.299
"It's okay"?

27:47.333 --> 27:50.135
You got a pool. What more do you want?

27:50.170 --> 27:52.304
- I guess.
- You guess?

27:52.338 --> 27:53.639
You guess?

27:53.673 --> 27:56.909
Well, you want to come out of there?

27:56.943 --> 27:58.844
No! I'm staying.

27:58.878 --> 28:00.546
Well, you want me
to come in there and get you?

28:00.580 --> 28:03.549
I can't have you in a pool that's only okay.

28:03.583 --> 28:05.150
[Laughing] It's good, it's good!

28:05.185 --> 28:07.853
[Laughs]

28:07.887 --> 28:09.755
You sure?

28:09.789 --> 28:11.423
You sure?

28:11.457 --> 28:13.525
I'm sure.

28:18.097 --> 28:21.900
♪

28:53.633 --> 28:56.301
Kaylee, honey, it's time to come out now.

28:56.336 --> 28:58.070
Just a few more minutes.

28:58.118 --> 28:59.885
No, you do what Pop-Pop says.

29:00.499 --> 29:01.699
Come on, baby.

29:01.733 --> 29:03.601
Before you turn into a prune.

29:03.635 --> 29:07.371
♪

29:18.416 --> 29:22.186
[ <i> "I Continue to Smile"</i> plays in background]

29:42.007 --> 29:45.743
[Indistinct conversation]

29:52.751 --> 29:56.520
[Music continues]

30:02.894 --> 30:05.896
[Sighs]

30:05.931 --> 30:09.700
[Music continues]

30:37.829 --> 30:39.897
Miss?

30:39.931 --> 30:41.632
The gentleman would like me to let you know

30:41.666 --> 30:43.000
that your next drink is on him.

30:44.102 --> 30:46.070
Just let me know when you're ready.

30:46.104 --> 30:49.840
[Music continues]

31:13.198 --> 31:16.133
I'm ready.

31:25.710 --> 31:27.578
Wasn't sure that was gonna work.

31:27.612 --> 31:29.079
[Chuckles]

31:29.114 --> 31:31.282
Don't tell me that's
the first time you've done that.

31:32.284 --> 31:33.918
So, what kind of return on investment

31:33.952 --> 31:35.419
are you getting on these drinks?

31:35.453 --> 31:36.820
Mm.

31:36.855 --> 31:38.956
None as pretty as you.

31:38.990 --> 31:41.091
Oh, man. [Chuckles]

31:41.126 --> 31:43.694
[Both laugh]

31:45.363 --> 31:49.266
I'm Dale, by the way.

31:49.301 --> 31:51.302
Giselle.

32:03.048 --> 32:05.349
Okay, item number 44.

32:05.383 --> 32:06.650
What do we have?

32:06.685 --> 32:08.052
[Sighs]

32:08.086 --> 32:12.323
Residency contract for Abigail Hildreth.

32:16.227 --> 32:18.162
Abigail Hildreth.

32:18.196 --> 32:21.498
And what's the date on that?

32:21.533 --> 32:24.802
Dated August 1, 1999.

32:24.836 --> 32:28.305
August 1, 1999.

32:28.340 --> 32:31.508
August 1, 1999.

32:31.543 --> 32:33.477
And do we have the corresponding
deposition for Mrs. Hildreth?

32:33.511 --> 32:36.113
Yes.

32:39.684 --> 32:41.352
[Sighs]

32:48.126 --> 32:49.927
[Clears throat]

32:53.131 --> 32:55.265
Have you ever heard the expression

32:55.300 --> 32:57.134
"a watched pot never boils"?

33:01.773 --> 33:05.175
Oh. Here it is.

33:05.210 --> 33:07.478
Thank you. See?

33:08.580 --> 33:11.548
I've got her down as item 12.

33:11.583 --> 33:14.585
Date of depo, September 15th.

33:14.619 --> 33:16.186
September 15th.

33:16.221 --> 33:18.022
15th of September.

33:18.056 --> 33:19.590
September 15th.

33:19.624 --> 33:22.292
Or, yeah, September 15th.

33:22.327 --> 33:23.560
Thank you.

33:23.595 --> 33:25.929
Okay, item number 45.

33:25.964 --> 33:29.733
[Cellphone vibrating]

33:31.603 --> 33:33.137
Jimmy.

33:33.171 --> 33:35.973
Oh, it's my grandma.

33:36.007 --> 33:37.608
She's old.

33:37.642 --> 33:39.710
Be right back.

33:39.744 --> 33:41.378
Kim?

33:41.413 --> 33:43.814
KIM: How fast can you get downtown?

33:43.848 --> 33:45.382
Uh, Santa Fe downtown?

33:45.417 --> 33:48.118
- Albuquerque.
- Why?

33:48.153 --> 33:49.787
I'm at the bar at Forque.

33:49.821 --> 33:51.989
And I've got a live one on the hook.

33:52.023 --> 33:53.357
[Chuckles]

33:56.194 --> 33:58.162
I'm on my way.

33:58.196 --> 34:00.397
What's the shot?

34:00.432 --> 34:01.765
DALE: Definitely two or three.

34:01.800 --> 34:03.067
You don't think they do?

34:03.101 --> 34:04.601
- Well, you know...
- They could.

34:04.636 --> 34:06.403
I know, but they don't have to. [Laughs]

34:06.438 --> 34:08.272
We get it.

34:08.306 --> 34:10.674
It's possible,

34:10.708 --> 34:12.909
but I don't understand why that's an issue.

34:12.944 --> 34:14.610
- Yeah. Yeah, yeah, yeah.
- It can always go bad.

34:14.646 --> 34:18.815
Yeah, yeah. [Giggles]

34:18.850 --> 34:20.951
- Oh, Viktor, there you are.
- So sorry I'm late.

34:20.985 --> 34:23.020
- I had to put out a few fires.
- Not a problem.

34:23.054 --> 34:25.022
I made a new friend.
Dale, my brother, Viktor.

34:25.056 --> 34:27.357
- Hey, how ya doing?
- Oh, nice to meet you, Dale.

34:27.391 --> 34:29.460
- Thanks for keeping sis company.
- My pleasure.

34:29.494 --> 34:30.994
You need a drink.

34:31.029 --> 34:33.197
Let's get you a drink.

34:33.231 --> 34:35.632
So, what do you do, Dale?

34:35.667 --> 34:37.134
I'm an engineer.

34:37.168 --> 34:40.804
What, like Casey Jones, with the hat and...

34:40.839 --> 34:42.539
[Laughing] No, idiot!

34:42.574 --> 34:45.208
An <i> engineer</i> engineer, not an "engineer."

34:45.243 --> 34:46.010
Dale builds things.

34:46.031 --> 34:47.531
I design things... spillways
and drainage fields, mostly.

34:48.379 --> 34:50.013
I don't... I don't actually build them.

34:50.047 --> 34:51.614
Well, that's cool, yeah.

34:51.649 --> 34:53.317
But you could still
wear the hat, though, right?

34:53.351 --> 34:55.452
[Both laugh] I mean, nothin stoppin' ya.

34:55.487 --> 34:57.221
Oh, yeah, I guess I could.

34:57.255 --> 34:59.323
I'm just saying, there's no rule
about that, as far as I know.

34:59.357 --> 35:01.225
Hey, you're such a brat. Why the good mood?

35:01.259 --> 35:03.460
Did it... go well today?

35:03.495 --> 35:06.330
Please tell me it went well.

35:06.364 --> 35:08.532
Yeah, it went well.

35:08.566 --> 35:11.668
Very well? Like, very, very...?

35:11.703 --> 35:13.804
Beyond our wildest, uh...

35:13.838 --> 35:15.572
Yeah. [Both laugh]

35:15.607 --> 35:17.040
Whoo! [Chuckles]

35:17.075 --> 35:18.542
How many of these has she had?

35:18.576 --> 35:20.244
Mm! I am just getting started, baby.

35:20.278 --> 35:21.678
[Laughs]

35:21.713 --> 35:23.380
- Remember these faces, Dale.
- Giselle.

35:23.414 --> 35:24.982
They are gonna be on the cover
of <i> Fortune</i> magazine,

35:25.016 --> 35:26.416
- January issue.
- Giselle, please.

35:26.451 --> 35:27.318
No, Dale's a good guy.
He's not gonna do anything.

35:27.348 --> 35:29.249
- Yeah, you're boring the man.
- Oh, no, no, not really.

35:30.388 --> 35:31.889
Thank you.

35:31.923 --> 35:34.925
All right, I am off
to the little girl's room.

35:34.959 --> 35:38.862
Say only nice things about me
while I'm gone, okay?

35:38.897 --> 35:41.265
[Sighs]

35:41.299 --> 35:44.902
She's something.

35:44.936 --> 35:47.671
Yeah.

35:47.705 --> 35:49.940
[Musetta's <i> "Red Star"</i> plays in background]

35:49.974 --> 35:52.910
So, Giselle was telling me
you two are starting a business.

35:54.479 --> 35:56.780
What exactly did she tell you?

35:56.814 --> 35:58.382
Oh, nothing much.

35:58.416 --> 36:00.217
Just something about a dot com,

36:00.251 --> 36:02.719
some way for people
to hook up with each other

36:02.754 --> 36:04.188
using the Internet?

36:04.222 --> 36:05.556
[Sighs]

36:05.590 --> 36:07.791
Oh, look, I'm sure you're a nice guy,

36:07.825 --> 36:10.427
but she was talking out of school.

36:10.461 --> 36:13.397
- We're... We're full up on this thing.
- Oh. Oh, okay.

36:13.431 --> 36:15.132
We sign one more investor,

36:15.166 --> 36:17.367
we got to go public, and I'm just...

36:17.402 --> 36:19.303
No. [Chuckles]

36:19.337 --> 36:22.940
We cannot take anyone else on.

36:22.974 --> 36:24.441
No offense.

36:24.475 --> 36:26.977
Oh, it's okay. Yeah.

36:29.781 --> 36:33.317
No worries.

36:33.351 --> 36:36.954
[Music continues]

36:38.891 --> 36:41.526
[Crickets chirping]

36:45.437 --> 36:49.140
[Brakes squeal]

36:49.174 --> 36:50.675
[Gearshift clicks]

36:50.709 --> 36:52.176
[Car door creaks]

36:54.379 --> 36:57.181
[Keys jingle]

36:57.216 --> 36:58.683
[Car door creaks]

36:58.717 --> 37:00.985
[Hip-hop music playing in background]

37:08.827 --> 37:10.027
[Music stops]

37:10.062 --> 37:11.729
[Dog barking in distance]

37:19.171 --> 37:20.371
[Lock disengages]

37:20.405 --> 37:22.306
[Door creaks]

37:24.676 --> 37:28.246
Spread your arms.

37:35.521 --> 37:37.855
[Speaking Spanish]

37:37.890 --> 37:39.390
No.

37:39.424 --> 37:42.293
[Speaking Spanish]

37:42.327 --> 37:43.528
He's got a gun.

37:43.562 --> 37:47.064
I don't care about the gun.

38:39.217 --> 38:44.121
Tomorrow, you go to the district attorney,

38:44.156 --> 38:49.360
and you explain to him
that my nephew's gun was yours.

38:49.394 --> 38:51.429
The D.A. will ask you,

38:51.463 --> 38:54.465
"Why you didn't say anything before?"

38:54.499 --> 38:57.568
You tell him you forgot, you were rattled...

38:57.603 --> 38:59.604
make up anything you want.

38:59.638 --> 39:01.305
I don't give a shit.

39:01.340 --> 39:03.641
But it's your gun.

39:05.243 --> 39:07.778
Let's discuss my payment.

39:07.813 --> 39:10.114
Mm, that time is past.

39:10.148 --> 39:11.882
No $5,000 for you.

39:11.917 --> 39:13.818
The price is $50,000.

39:13.852 --> 39:16.754
How about the payment is you get to live?

39:16.788 --> 39:18.089
Not enough.

39:18.123 --> 39:21.826
Oh, you think you can negotiate with me?

39:21.860 --> 39:26.330
I say the word, my nephews
go to a certain motel,

39:26.365 --> 39:28.332
pay a visit to your daughter-in-law

39:28.367 --> 39:30.101
and your little granddaughter.

39:30.135 --> 39:33.804
What do you think happens then?

39:33.839 --> 39:38.676
Consider your position carefully.

39:38.710 --> 39:40.511
I get my money...

39:40.545 --> 39:44.181
or neither of us walk out of here.

39:54.059 --> 39:57.495
You willing to die for this?

39:59.564 --> 40:03.701
Maybe I need the $50,000 more than you do.

40:07.806 --> 40:11.542
[Laughing]

40:11.576 --> 40:15.046
[Speaking Spanish]

40:16.815 --> 40:22.720
How you manage to live so long
with a mouth like that, hmm?

40:25.490 --> 40:27.658
$50,000.

40:29.227 --> 40:32.229
And the gun is yours.

40:39.104 --> 40:42.006
[Crickets chirping]

40:48.580 --> 40:51.749
[Vehicle approaches]

40:51.783 --> 40:53.384
[Engine shuts off]

40:53.418 --> 40:55.352
[Vehicle door opens, closes]

41:04.196 --> 41:07.698
[Door creaks]

41:10.869 --> 41:14.338
- He sent you?
- I volunteered.

41:14.372 --> 41:17.074
Only safe way for us to talk.

41:20.145 --> 41:23.114
[Door creaks]

41:33.825 --> 41:36.927
You really pushed it in there.

41:41.299 --> 41:43.300
That thing we did...

41:44.302 --> 41:47.404
he finds out, we're both dead.

41:47.439 --> 41:49.607
You get that, right?

41:49.641 --> 41:51.642
What thing we did?

41:56.815 --> 41:58.215
What's this?

41:58.250 --> 41:59.550
$25,000.

41:59.584 --> 42:00.785
What for?

42:00.819 --> 42:02.419
We made a deal.

42:02.454 --> 42:05.156
I didn't hold up my end.

42:06.158 --> 42:10.761
Your problem is coming back
sooner than we expected.

42:28.280 --> 42:29.947
You gonna cash that?

42:29.981 --> 42:32.783
I might know a guy who can help.

42:32.818 --> 42:35.219
It's better as a souvenir.

42:35.253 --> 42:38.889
I figured you'd be maybe... I don't know...

42:38.924 --> 42:41.559
a touch happier this morning.

42:41.593 --> 42:43.928
Maybe a smidge, possibly?

42:43.962 --> 42:46.497
I am. I'm totally happy.

42:46.531 --> 42:48.332
Why wouldn't I be?

42:50.335 --> 42:51.969
I, uh...

42:53.538 --> 42:55.973
I had a job offer.

42:56.007 --> 42:58.475
Really? From where?

42:58.510 --> 43:00.945
Schweikart and Cokely.

43:00.979 --> 43:02.346
Seriously?

43:02.380 --> 43:04.515
Rich Schweikart said
that they would even pay off

43:04.549 --> 43:06.784
my law-school loans.

43:06.818 --> 43:08.419
That's great.

43:08.453 --> 43:10.588
Please let me be there when you tell Howard.

43:10.622 --> 43:12.323
Please.

43:12.357 --> 43:15.092
So why the sad puppy eyes?
What, you don't want that job?

43:15.126 --> 43:16.861
No, no, o-of course I do.

43:16.895 --> 43:18.362
I mean, who wouldn't, right?

43:18.396 --> 43:19.763
[Scoffs] It's a huge firm.

43:19.798 --> 43:21.765
You get out from under Howard's thumb.

43:21.800 --> 43:23.133
Right. Exactly.

43:23.168 --> 43:25.836
Besides, HHM is looking more and more like

43:25.871 --> 43:27.872
a dead end for me, anyway.

43:27.906 --> 43:30.174
Exactly. So what's the problem?

43:30.208 --> 43:33.010
I just...

43:35.814 --> 43:37.815
[Chuckles]

43:37.849 --> 43:40.384
I don't know.

43:40.418 --> 43:43.821
I keep thinking of you
floating in that pool.

43:45.023 --> 43:48.726
You knew what you wanted,
but I got in the way.

43:48.760 --> 43:51.161
What are you talking about?

43:51.196 --> 43:55.199
You took the Davis & Main job because of me.

43:55.233 --> 43:58.702
I took that job because
it was the right decision.

43:58.737 --> 44:00.804
A steady paycheck... done.

44:00.839 --> 44:04.875
A place to live that's more
than, oh, 5 square feet... boom.

44:04.910 --> 44:07.811
A car that's all one color... nailed it.

44:07.846 --> 44:09.313
[Chuckles] I'm good.

44:09.347 --> 44:10.681
I got what I wanted.

44:10.715 --> 44:12.816
And you, with the Schweikart thing?

44:12.851 --> 44:15.986
You could have everything <i> you</i> ever wanted.

44:16.021 --> 44:18.422
What's not to love about that?

44:18.456 --> 44:20.691
Yeah.

44:20.725 --> 44:24.361
What's not to love? [Chuckles]

44:28.566 --> 44:31.402
[Car alarm chirps]

44:31.436 --> 44:35.239
[The Bombay Royale's <i>"Henna Henna"</i> plays]

44:35.273 --> 44:39.243
- ♪<i> Lok bole paap hobe</i> ♪
- [Car alarm chirps]

